<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="NAME"
>NAME <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<p>Moose::Policy - Moose-mounted police</p>

<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="SYNOPSIS"
>SYNOPSIS <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<pre class="sh_perl">  package Foo;

  use Moose::Policy &#39;Moose::Policy::FollowPBP&#39;;
  use Moose;

  has &#39;bar&#39; =&#62; (is =&#62; &#39;rw&#39;, default =&#62; &#39;Foo::bar&#39;);
  has &#39;baz&#39; =&#62; (is =&#62; &#39;ro&#39;, default =&#62; &#39;Foo::baz&#39;);

  # Foo now has (get, set)_bar methods as well as get_baz</pre>

<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="DEPRECATION_NOTICE"
>DEPRECATION NOTICE <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<p><b>Moose::Policy is deprecated</b>.</p>

<p><a href="/perldoc?MooseX%3A%3AFollowPBP" class="podlinkpod"
>MooseX::FollowPBP</a> replaces the <a href="/~drolsky/Moose-Policy-0.05/lib/Moose/Policy/FollowPBP.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>Moose::Policy::FollowPBP</a> module. The other policies included in this distribution do not yet have standalone MooseX modules, as of November, 2010.</p>

<p>This module has not passed its tests since Moose 1.05, and will probably not be fixed.</p>

<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="DESCRIPTION"
>DESCRIPTION <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<p>This module allows you to specify your project-wide or even company-wide Moose meta-policy.</p>

<p>Most all of Moose&#39;s features can be customized through the use of custom metaclasses, however fiddling with the metaclasses can be hairy. Moose::Policy removes most of that hairiness and makes it possible to cleanly contain a set of meta-level customizations in one easy to use module.</p>

<p>This is still an release of this module and it should not be considered to be complete by any means. It is very basic implemenation at this point and will likely get more feature-full over time, as people request features. So if you have a suggestion/need/idea, please speak up.</p>

<h2><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="What_is_a_meta-policy?"
>What is a meta-policy?</a></h2>

<p>A meta-policy is a set of custom Moose metaclasses which can be used to implement a number of customizations and restrictions on a particular Moose class.</p>

<p>For instance, <a href="/~drolsky/Moose-Policy-0.05/lib/Moose/Policy/SingleInheritence.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>Moose::Policy::SingleInheritence</a> enforces that all specified Moose classes can only use single inheritance. It does this by trapping the call to <code>superclasses</code> on the metaclass and only allowing you to assign a single superclass.</p>

<p>The <a href="/~drolsky/Moose-Policy-0.05/lib/Moose/Policy/FollowPBP.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>Moose::Policy::FollowPBP</a> policy changes the default behavior of accessors to fit the recomendations found in Perl Best Practices.</p>

<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="CAVEATS"
>CAVEATS <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<h2><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="Always_load_Moose::Policy_first."
>Always load Moose::Policy first.</a></h2>

<p>You <b>must</b> put the following line of code:</p>

<pre class="sh_perl">  use Moose::Policy &#39;My::Policy&#39;;</pre>

<p>before this line:</p>

<pre class="sh_perl">  use Moose;</pre>

<p>This is because Moose::Policy must be given the opportunity to set the custom metaclass before Moose has set it&#39;s default metaclass. In fact, if you try to set a Moose::Policy and there is a <code>meta</code> method available, not only will kittens die, but your program will too.</p>

<h2><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="Policies_are_class_scoped"
>Policies are class scoped</a></h2>

<p>You must repeat the policy for each class you want to use it. It is <b>not</b> inherited. This may change in the future, probably it will be a Moose::Policy itself to allow Moose policies to be inherited.</p>

<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="THE_POLICY"
>THE POLICY <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<p>A Policy is set by passing <code>Moose::Policy::import()</code> a package name. This package is then queried for what metaclasses it should use. The possible metaclass values are:</p>

<dl>
<dt><a name="metaclass"
><b>metaclass</b></a></dt>

<dd>
<p>This defaults to <code>Moose::Meta::Class</code>.</p>

<dt><a name="attribute_metaclass"
><b>attribute_metaclass</b></a></dt>

<dd>
<dt><a name="instance_metaclass"
><b>instance_metaclass</b></a></dt>

<dd>
<dt><a name="method_metaclass"
><b>method_metaclass</b></a></dt>
</dl>

<p>For examples of what a Policy actually looks like see the examples in <code>Moose::Policy::</code> and the test suite. More docs to come on this later (probably a cookbook or something).</p>

<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="METHODS"
>METHODS <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<dl>
